<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-548-706  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 548 706.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DEC User  May 1990 p49(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Are employers living in the Middle Ages? (Skills shortage 1)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Eastwood, Alison.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The UK has 50,000 more information systems jobs than trainedpersonnel.andP;  A 1989 sample of 468 computing personnel showed thatonly 3 percent said they left their jobs to begin contracting; therest changed jobs because of job opportunities at other companies.andO;The demand can be met in several ways, one of which is training.andO;But UK companies spend less than 1 percent of their revenue ontraining and over 50 percent do not provide any training at all.andO;Companies prefer to recruit rather than train, but this may beshortsighted because it does not take into account thatrecruitment may be more expensive than training, nor thereorientation the new employee must undergo.andP;  The BBC2 documentary9 II 5 reported that countries which focus on training, such asJapan and Germany, have workforces that are more productive andcan produce goods more cheaply.andP;  DEC is involved in a series ofprograms that emphasize re-education as well as re-skilling.andP;  AJan 1990 report from the Institute of Manpower Services says thatout of 912,000 additional employees looking for work between 1990and 1995, 83 percent (761,000) will be women.andP;  DEC has projectsthat focus on girls still in school, on older women entering theworkforce for the first time, and on women returning to work.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (training).andO;Topic:     TrainingPersonnelManagement of EDPUnited Kingdom.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>